#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:58
msgid "Client-side cursors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:60
msgid ""
"Client-side cursors are what Psycopg uses in its normal querying process. "
"They are implemented by the `Cursor` and `AsyncCursor` classes. In such "
"querying pattern, after a cursor sends a query to the server (usually "
"calling `~Cursor.execute()`), the server replies transferring to the client "
"the whole set of results requested, which is stored in the state of the same "
"cursor and from where it can be read from Python code (using methods such as "
"`~Cursor.fetchone()` and siblings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:68
msgid ""
"This querying process is very scalable because, after a query result has "
"been transmitted to the client, the server doesn't keep any state. Because "
"the results are already in the client memory, iterating its rows is very "
"quick."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:72
msgid ""
"The downside of this querying method is that the entire result has to be "
"transmitted completely to the client (with a time proportional to its size) "
"and the client needs enough memory to hold it, so it is only suitable for "
"reasonably small result sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:84
msgid "Client-side-binding cursors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:88
msgid ""
"The previously described :ref:`client-side cursors <client-side-cursors>` "
"send the query and the parameters separately to the server. This is the most "
"efficient way to process parametrised queries and allows to build several "
"features and optimizations. However, not all types of queries can be bound "
"server-side; in particular no Data Definition Language query can. See :ref:"
"`server-side-binding` for the description of these problems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:95
msgid ""
"The `ClientCursor` (and its `AsyncClientCursor` async counterpart) merge the "
"query on the client and send the query and the parameters merged together to "
"the server. This allows to parametrize any type of PostgreSQL statement, not "
"only queries (:sql:`SELECT`) and Data Manipulation statements (:sql:"
"`INSERT`, :sql:`UPDATE`, :sql:`DELETE`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:101
msgid ""
"Using `!ClientCursor`, Psycopg 3 behaviour will be more similar to "
"`psycopg2` (which only implements client-side binding) and could be useful "
"to port Psycopg 2 programs more easily to Psycopg 3. The objects in the "
"`sql` module allow for greater flexibility (for instance to parametrize a "
"table name too, not only values); however, for simple cases, a `!"
"ClientCursor` could be the right object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:108
msgid ""
"In order to obtain `!ClientCursor` from a connection, you can set its "
"`~Connection.cursor_factory` (at init time or changing its attribute "
"afterwards):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:112
msgid ""
"from psycopg import connect, ClientCursor\n"
"\n"
"conn = psycopg.connect(DSN, cursor_factory=ClientCursor)\n"
"cur = conn.cursor()\n"
"# <psycopg.ClientCursor [no result] [IDLE] (database=piro) at 0x7fd977ae2880>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:120
msgid ""
"If you need to create a one-off client-side-binding cursor out of a normal "
"connection, you can just use the `~ClientCursor` class passing the "
"connection as argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:124
msgid ""
"conn = psycopg.connect(DSN)\n"
"cur = psycopg.ClientCursor(conn)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:132
msgid ""
"Client-side cursors don't support :ref:`binary parameters and return values "
"<binary-data>` and don't support :ref:`prepared statements <prepared-"
"statements>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:138
msgid ""
"The best use for client-side binding cursors is probably to port large "
"Psycopg 2 code to Psycopg 3, especially for programs making wide use of Data "
"Definition Language statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:142
msgid ""
"The `psycopg.sql` module allows for more generic client-side query "
"composition, to mix client- and server-side parameters binding, and allows "
"to parametrize tables and fields names too, or entirely generic SQL snippets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:155
msgid "Simple query protocol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:157
msgid ""
"Using the `!ClientCursor` should ensure that psycopg will always use the "
"`simple query protocol`__ for querying. In most cases, the choice of the "
"frontend/backend protocol used is transparent on PostgreSQL. However, in "
"some case using the simple query protocol is mandatory. This is the case "
"querying the `PgBouncer admin console`__ for instance, which doesn't support "
"the extended query protocol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:167
msgid ""
"from psycopg import connect, ClientCursor\n"
"\n"
"conn = psycopg.connect(ADMIN_DSN, cursor_factory=ClientCursor)\n"
"cur = conn.cursor()\n"
"cur.execute(\"SHOW STATS\")\n"
"cur.fetchall()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:176
msgid ""
"While querying using the `!ClientCursor` works well with PgBouncer, the "
"connection's COMMIT and ROLLBACK commands are only ensured to be executed "
"using the simple query protocol starting from Psycopg 3.1.20."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:181
msgid ""
"In previous versions you should use an autocommit connection in order to "
"query the PgBouncer admin console:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:184
msgid ""
"from psycopg import connect, ClientCursor\n"
"\n"
"conn = psycopg.connect(ADMIN_DSN, cursor_factory=ClientCursor, "
"autocommit=True)\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:200
msgid "Server-side cursors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:202
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL has its own concept of *cursor* too (sometimes also called "
"*portal*). When a database cursor is created, the query is not necessarily "
"completely processed: the server might be able to produce results only as "
"they are needed. Only the results requested are transmitted to the client: "
"if the query result is very large but the client only needs the first few "
"records it is possible to transmit only them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:209
msgid ""
"The downside is that the server needs to keep track of the partially "
"processed results, so it uses more memory and resources on the server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:212
msgid ""
"Psycopg allows the use of server-side cursors using the classes "
"`ServerCursor` and `AsyncServerCursor`. They are usually created by passing "
"the `!name` parameter to the `~Connection.cursor()` method (reason for "
"which, in `!psycopg2`, they are usually called *named cursors*). The use of "
"these classes is similar to their client-side counterparts: their interface "
"is the same, but behind the scene they send commands to control the state of "
"the cursor on the server (for instance when fetching new records or when "
"moving using `~Cursor.scroll()`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:221
msgid ""
"Using a server-side cursor it is possible to process datasets larger than "
"what would fit in the client's memory. However for small queries they are "
"less efficient because it takes more commands to receive their result, so "
"you should use them only if you need to process huge results or if only a "
"partial result is needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:229
msgid ""
"Server-side cursors are created and managed by `ServerCursor` using SQL "
"commands such as DECLARE_, FETCH_, MOVE_. The PostgreSQL documentation gives "
"a good idea of what is possible to do with them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:241
msgid "\"Stealing\" an existing cursor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:243
msgid ""
"A Psycopg `ServerCursor` can be also used to consume a cursor which was "
"created in other ways than the :sql:`DECLARE` that `ServerCursor.execute()` "
"runs behind the scene."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:247
msgid "For instance if you have a `PL/pgSQL function returning a cursor`__:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:251
msgid ""
"CREATE FUNCTION reffunc(refcursor) RETURNS refcursor AS $$\n"
"BEGIN\n"
"    OPEN $1 FOR SELECT col FROM test;\n"
"    RETURN $1;\n"
"END;\n"
"$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:260
msgid ""
"you can run a one-off command in the same connection to call it (e.g. using "
"`Connection.execute()`) in order to create the cursor on the server:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:263
msgid "conn.execute(\"SELECT reffunc('curname')\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:267
msgid ""
"after which you can create a server-side cursor declared by the same name, "
"and directly call the fetch methods, skipping the `~ServerCursor.execute()` "
"call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:270
msgid ""
"cur = conn.cursor('curname')\n"
"# no cur.execute()\n"
"for record in cur:  # or cur.fetchone(), cur.fetchmany()...\n"
"    # do something with record"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:281
msgid "Raw query cursors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:285
msgid ""
"The `RawCursor` and `AsyncRawCursor` classes allow users to use PostgreSQL "
"native placeholders (``$1``, ``$2``, etc.) in their queries instead of the "
"standard ``%s`` placeholder. This can be useful when it's desirable to pass "
"the query unmodified to PostgreSQL and rely on PostgreSQL's placeholder "
"functionality, such as when dealing with a very complex query containing "
"``%s`` inside strings, dollar-quoted strings or elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:292
msgid ""
"One important note is that raw query cursors only accept positional "
"arguments in the form of a list or tuple. This means you cannot use named "
"arguments (i.e., dictionaries)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:296
msgid ""
"`!RawCursor` behaves like `Cursor`, in returning the complete result from "
"the server to the client. The `RawServerCursor` and `AsyncRawServerCursor` "
"implement :ref:`server-side-cursors` with raw PostgreSQL placeholders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:300
msgid "There are two ways to use raw query cursors:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:302
msgid "Using the cursor factory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:304
msgid ""
"from psycopg import connect, RawCursor\n"
"\n"
"with connect(dsn, cursor_factory=RawCursor) as conn:\n"
"    with conn.cursor() as cur:\n"
"        cur.execute(\"SELECT $1, $2\", [1, \"Hello\"])\n"
"        assert cur.fetchone() == (1, \"Hello\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:313
msgid "Instantiating a cursor:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cursors.rst:315
msgid ""
"from psycopg import connect, RawCursor\n"
"\n"
"with connect(dsn) as conn:\n"
"    with RawCursor(conn) as cur:\n"
"        cur.execute(\"SELECT $1, $2\", [1, \"Hello\"])\n"
"        assert cur.fetchone() == (1, \"Hello\")"
msgstr ""

